<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900424-0028</DOCNO><DOCID>900424-0028.</DOCID><HL>   What's News --   Business and Finance</HL><DATE>04/24/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A1</SO><LP>   SIR JAMES GOLDSMITH dropped his pursuit of B.A.TIndustries, thwarted by growing opposition to highlyleveraged hostile takeovers. The financier, whose initial$21.13 billion bid for B.A.T was the second-largest inhistory, faced obstacles in several U.S. states where theBritish giant had operations. The final blow apparently wasCalifornia's recent decision to bar a change in control ofB.A.T's Farmers Insurance unit.   ---</LP><TEXT>   General Motors expects to shut a Michigan assembly plantin 1993, the latest in a series of closings due to slowingsales. The UAW union has vowed to make job security a topissue in coming contract talks with GM.                                                                                                          The Supreme Court refused to hear an appeal by GM over awarranty-related suit that may become a class action fornearly 600,000 customers.   ---   ATandamp;T senior debt totaling $9.2 billion was upgraded byMoody's, the first ratings boost since the 1984 breakup ofthe Bell system.   ---   The IRS may be reluctant to loosen a tax regulation thatsome investors say thwarts free trade in debt securities. Thedecision, expected this week, involves reviving bearer bonds.   ---   Exxon's profit fell 29% in the first quarter due toone-time items, while Amoco's net rose 1.7%. Higher oilprices boosted exploration and production results at bothfirms but hurt chemical and refining margins.   ---   Stock prices sank amid continued worries about higherinterest rates, while bond prices fell modestly. The DowJones industrials closed off 29.28 points, at 2666.67. Thedollar rose.                                                                                                          Oil prices continued to rebound on speculation that OPECmay agree soon to curb its overproduction.   ---   Coca-Cola is moving into East Germany with a $140 millioninvestment. The soft-drink giant hopes to match its successin West Germany.   ---   A key Gulf Power witness pleaded guilty to contempt andtax charges. Ray Howell also agreed to cooperate with thefederal probe of political contributions by the Southernunit.   ---   Three Asian nations were accused by the U.S. of exportingmore than $1 billion of synthetic-fiber sweaters to Americaat unfairly low prices.   ---   Time Warner posted a $51 million loss for the firstquarter, reflecting the continued cost of its merger lastyear. The company said earnings hit a record if those costsare excluded.   ---   A proxy fight will be reviewed by the Supreme Court todetermine if shareholders may sue under federal law formisleading proxy statements.   ---   A group of disabled people has joined forces with homebuilders to oppose proposed guidelines to make apartmentbuildings more accessible.   ---   Markets --   Stocks: Volume 136,150,000 shares. Dow Jones industrials2666.67, off 29.28; transportation 1141.36, off 13.51;utilities 205.67, off 2.52.   Bonds: Shearson Lehman Hutton Treasury index 3232.23, off4.39.   Commodities: Dow Jones futures index 134.17, up 0.24; spotindex 135.34, off 0.67.   Dollar: 157.60 yen, up 0.15; 1.6995 marks, up 0.0120.</TEXT></DOC>